# Fluff Date: 2026-02-12 20:24:28
overview:<p>The Exhumer is a fifty-five-ton medium BattleMech developed by Independence Weaponry on Quentin during the waning years of the Republic of the Sphere. Heavily championed by Benjamin District Warlord Mitsura Sakamoto, who held several engineering degrees, the design was intended to become the Draconis Combine Mustered Soldiery's next standard BattleMech, supplanting aging workhorses like the Dragon and Thunderbolt in front-line service. First entering production in 3129, the Exhumer was conceived as a long-range fire support platform mounted on a fast and well-protected medium chassis. However, persistent targeting system failures during early combat operations led the DCMS to cancel its remaining orders, redirecting production toward the mercenary market where the design found a far more receptive audience.</p>

capabilities:<p>Built around a Hermes 330 XL engine, the Exhumer achieves a top speed of 97 kph, making it one of the faster designs in its weight class. An EXR endo steel frame maximizes available payload, while ten and a half tons of New Samarkand Royal ferro-fibrous armor supplemented by CASE II ammunition protection gives the design solid survivability for its tonnage. The absence of jump jets reflects the intended role as a mobile fire support platform rather than a close-range brawler.</p><p>The primary armament consists of a pair of Diverse Optics 30X extended-range large lasers mounted in the arms, providing significant long-range striking power. These are supported by twin LongFire V LRM-5 launchers and a Shigunga MRM-10, offering supplemental missile fire at varying engagement distances. However, the integration of surplus Garret communications and targeting systems proved to be the design's greatest weakness. Poor synchronization between the Garret D2j targeting system and the multiple missile launchers resulted in persistent accuracy problems that plagued early production models. The Exhumer's loadout clearly favors stand-off engagements, making the inclusion of prominent battle fists something of a design contradiction, though mercenary operators have found these melee weapons surprisingly useful when engagements close unexpectedly.</p>

deployment:<p>Developed by Independence Weaponry specifically for the mercenary market beginning in 3131, this variant completely reworks the Exhumer for short-range combat. The arm-mounted extended-range large lasers are replaced with large pulse lasers, trading raw range for improved accuracy at closer engagement distances. The original missile array is removed in favor of three SRM-2 launchers distributed across the torso sections, supplemented by a center-torso-mounted extended-range small laser. The defining feature of the EXR-3P is its Triple Strength Myomer system, which dramatically enhances the 'Mech's physical combat capability when operating at elevated temperatures, transforming the Exhumer's battle fists from a design curiosity into a devastating close-quarters weapon. Two double heat sinks were removed to accommodate the myomer system, relying on combat heat to activate the TSM at optimal moments. The EXR-3P proved highly popular among mercenary commands, offering a radically different tactical profile from the troubled original while retaining the same reliable chassis and power plant.</p>

history:<p>The Exhumer's origins are inextricably linked to the political ambitions of Benjamin District Warlord Mitsura Sakamoto, who championed the design for over a decade before it finally entered production. Sakamoto, an engineer by training, became personally invested in the project and used his considerable political influence to push the Exhumer through the DCMS procurement process. When the first production models rolled off Independence Weaponry's lines on Quentin and were assigned to the Second Benjamin Regulars in 3129, Sakamoto's vision appeared close to realization.</p><p>Early deployments along the Dominion and Republic borders quickly revealed the Exhumer's critical flaw. The Garret-manufactured targeting and communications systems, sourced from surplus stocks, suffered from poor integration with the 'Mech's multiple missile systems. Combat reports from raids on worlds such as Dehgolan documented repeated targeting failures that left MechWarriors unable to reliably engage with their missile armament. These problems proved embarrassing enough that Sakamoto was forced to order a comprehensive electronic overhaul of all fielded Exhumers, a costly admission of the design's shortcomings.</p><p>The DCMS subsequently canceled its remaining Exhumer orders, and Independence Weaponry pivoted to marketing the design to mercenary buyers. This transition proved fortuitous for the manufacturer. Despite the targeting issues, the Exhumer was better received among mercenary forces who valued the chassis's speed, armor protection, and relatively affordable price point. Mercenary commands such as Gannon's Cannons employed the Exhumer effectively in strike and garrison operations across the Draconis Combine's frontier, demonstrating that the design had genuine combat potential when operated by experienced MechWarriors willing to work around its electronic shortcomings.</p><p>Operating from Quentin, which passed from Republic of the Sphere control to independent status and eventually Draconis Combine authority during the tumultuous Dark Age period, Independence Weaponry continued developing the chassis. The introduction of the close-combat-oriented EXR-3P variant in 3131 demonstrated the manufacturer's responsiveness to market demands, and the variant's popularity among mercenary commands helped rehabilitate the Exhumer's reputation. By the ilClan era, continued production under Combine oversight on Quentin ensured a steady supply of both variants to mercenary and Combine forces alike.</p>

